==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hone
<hw>Hone</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>honger</ets> to grumble. ⟦root⟧37.]</ety> <def>To grumble; pine;
lament; long.</def> <mark>[Dial.Eng. & Southern U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hone</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hone
<hw>Hone</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>h⟦umac⟧n</ets> a
knob.]</ety> <def>A kind of swelling in the cheek.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hone</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hone
<hw>Hone</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>h⟦amac⟧n</ets>; akin to
Icel. <ets>hein</ets>, OSw. <ets>hen</ets>; cf. Skr.
<ets>⟦cced⟧⟦amac⟧⟦nsdot⟧a</ets>, also <ets>⟦cced⟧⟦omac⟧</ets>,
<ets>⟦cced⟧i</ets>, to sharpen, and E. <ets>cone</ets>. ⟦root⟧38,
228.]</ety> <def>A stone of a fine grit, or a slab, as of metal, covered
with an abrading substance or powder, used for sharpening cutting
instruments, and especially for setting razors; an oilstone.</def>
<rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hone slate</b></col><cd>See <er>Polishing
slate</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hone stone</b></col>, <cd>one of several
kinds of stone used for hones. See <er>Novaculite</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hone</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hone
<hw>Hone</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Honed</conjf> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Honing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sharpen on, or
with, a hone; to rub on a hone in order to sharpen; <as>as, to
<ex>hone</ex> a razor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to render more precise or more effective; <as>as, to
<ex>hone</ex> one's skills</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Honest</ent>⟦br⟧
